File & Directory Commands

ls – List files and directories

ls -l – List files with details

ls -a – Show hidden files

pwd – Show current directory path

cd – Change directory

mkdir – Create a directory

rmdir – Delete empty directory

rm – Delete files

rm -r – Delete directory and contents

cp – Copy files or folders

mv – Move or rename files

touch – Create empty file

stat – Show file details

File Viewing & Editing

cat – Display file content

less – View file page by page

more – View file content

head – Show first lines of file

tail – Show last lines of file

tail -f – Monitor file changes

nano – Edit file using nano editor

vi – Edit file using vi editor

Permission & Ownership

chmod – Change file permissions

chown – Change file owner

chgrp – Change group ownership

System Information

uname – Show system information

uname -a – Show full system details

hostname – Show system hostname

uptime – Show system running time

df -h – Disk usage information

du -h – Folder size information

free -h – Memory usage

top – Show running processes

htop – Advanced process viewer

User & Process Management

whoami – Show current user

who – Show logged-in users

ps – Show running processes

kill – Stop a process

kill -9 – Force stop a process

Networking Commands

ip a – Show IP address

ping – Check network connectivity

netstat – Network status

ss – Show socket information

curl – Access URL data

wget – Download files from internet

Package & System Control

sudo – Run command as administrator

apt update – Update package list

apt install – Install software

reboot – Restart system

shutdown – Shutdown system

clear – Clear terminal screen

Conclusion

These 50 Linux commands are enough for:

File handling

User management

Networking

System monitoring

Server administration
